The band gap (E_g) is a fundamental electronic property that determines the suitability of materials for applications in electronics, photovoltaics, and optoelectronics. Traditional materials discovery relies on trial-and-error approaches or high-throughput experimental screening, which are time-consuming and resource-intensive. Here, we present a hybrid inverse design framework that combines neural network-based band gap prediction with Knowledge-Informed Genetic Algorithm (KIGA) to discover inorganic materials with targeted electronic properties. Our approach integrates the largest experimental band gap dataset compiled to date from Matbench and Zhuo et al. sources, comprising 6,489 unique compositions categorized into scientifically validated electronic categories. A robust neural network model was developed using 132 Magpie descriptors, achieving a mean absolute error (MAE) of 0.3329 eV and R² of 0.7650 on external validation. The inverse design algorithm incorporates chemical valence rules, stoichiometric constraints, and empirical stability criteria to generate chemically plausible candidates. For target band gaps of 0.0, 0.05, 0.8, 1.8, 2.5, and 4.0 eV, the method generated candidates with errors below 0.02 eV, many of which represent previously unreported compositions. Validation against the Materials Project database yielded a mean absolute error of 0.35 eV, demonstrating good agreement with DFT calculations. This work establishes an effective computational pipeline for accelerated discovery of functional materials with tailored electronic properties.
